e><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE006922%2F1"><gtr:id>CB15B443-30F5-421F-A0EA-E1122CEA7B61</gtr:id><gtr:title>Globalisation and New Religious Movements. Kabbalah Centres in Britain, France, Israel and Brazil.</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E006922/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Kabbalah Centres, the largest organization in the world dedicated to the teaching of Jewish Kabbalah, is a striking&amp;nbsp; example of the transformation of a non-proselytising ethnic religion into a global religious network. They were created in Israel during the 1960s by Philip Berg, a New-Yorker with a Jewish background.&amp;nbsp; Firstly, his religious teachings targeted &amp;quot;Jews alienated from their roots&amp;quot;, but then he claimed that his mission was to &amp;quot;spread and disseminate this knowledge to every human being, in whatever language, in whatever country&amp;quot;. The movement claims now that no fewer than 4 millions have visited one of the 50 centres in the world, half of whom are said to have no Jewish background.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The purpose of this research is twofold&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>To offer an innovative analysis of globalisation of religion based on empirical and cross-national investigations, with emphasis on the interaction between local and global. It will be based on empirical investigations of the Kabbalah Centres in Britain, France, Israel and Brazil 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>To contribute significantly to the sociology of New Religious Movements. The Kabbalah Centres never been analytically investigated, and more broadly the relations between Judaism and NRMs have hitherto largely been neglected.&lt;/li>
